text: Everyone, I actually I have a great storyline for this particular event. Please hear me out and leave negative and positive critique!  During the day of the scheduled annual Purge, a loyal, middle-classed father goes out to get the necessities for the particular event. While coming back he realizes that the security system has been locked by his family. He tries to organize his thoughts until he realizes that he has been betrayed by the ones he sought to love throughout his life.  As the alarm announcing the commencement of the Purge goes off he realizes that he has to withstand the night alone and as a participant of the event.  (He goes off battling out the enemies that come his way.. lalala.. regular action..)  Once the Purge is over he goes back to his family to see they are alive and well, the anxiety and anguish he has exalted takes the best of him and he slaughters the ones he loved.  Looking over, he experiences major acts of emotions taking in on what he did to his family. Running away from his property he goes to find a broken masks of one of the group who took a participation in the event in midst of a fire. He holds it in his hand reasoning with himself.  ENDING:  He comes to reason with himself to vow himself to be an annual participant of the purge. As his back faces the fire, he slowly puts on the mask.

text: This is nothing more than statist propaganda. Anarchy isn't lawless chaos, and people don't kill each other just because it's unlawful.  Would you, the person reading this comment, rob, rape, and/or murder your neighbors just because the politicians say they won't punish you for it? If you answered no, then you can count yourself amongst the overwhelming majority of the human race.  The sort of people who would only harm others if the government said they'd get away with it aren't experienced criminals, and are likely to fall victim to the tens of millions of armed Americans who'd defend themselves if attacked by these idiots. Even if you were successful, you'd face economic ostracization, and possibly even vigilante justice afterwards.  If the government declared a 12 hour lawless period, there'd be no more violent acts than usual. Private security, citizen militias, and armed neighborhood watchmen would do what they normally do with, or without government police who spend most of their time, and effect going after non criminals like drug users, and sellers of raw milk.

text: The thing about this premise is couldn't law enforcement just charge anyone with "conspiracy to commit (insert crime)"? Take any complex premeditated crime like bank robbery, assassination, drug trafficking, the type of things that couldn't be planned, prepared and carried out in a single night. I'd like to see how the movie would approach something like this. If the crime occurs within the time frame of the purge is it suppose to be like it and all actions relating to the crime never existed? If you stole a million dollars during the purge , could they come after when everything is over and get you for "possessing stolen property"? I hope they explore more of these 'what if' scenarios rather then just have another bunch of impulsive psychos running around hunting each other again. Â Â

text: Haven't watched this film yet (obviously) but I have a question here.Â  Do you really think putting "anarchy" here in the film's concept is logical?  I'm not an anarchist but as far as I know, they oppose the government in telling people how to live in society. Considering that people can kill anybody EXCEPT high government officials during the purge, don't you think that's IRONY of "ANARCHISM?" Tons of civilians are killed while high ranking officials sit in the comfort of their homes. I can't imagine anarchists participating in such activity by the government. Realistically, 12 hours is enough for people who hate the gov or the purge to bring down the gov or ROB A FREAKING BANK. :P Â   All systems are down. You have 364 days to plan. text: I don't understand why they make sequels to crappy movies. The Purge was the dumbest movie, I think Ethan Hawk's acting has peeked at Assault on Precinct 13. He could have shown way more emotion then he did. For the entire time of the movie, the "homeless guy" wore dog tags, and could fire a weapon. Yet, the entire movie, no one bothers to mention or notice his dog tags or think to ask him that. It would have been cooler, to have Hawk, talk to the guy, and find out he was in war, otherwise, why bother showing clearly visible military dog tags if no back story is coming from it. The decision to help him, should have come from Ethan Hawk's background character information, where he served in the military before the Purge started. That would have made an awesome movie moment where instead of pointing the gun at him, he hands the guy the gun, but no, we don't even get a clear definition of that. I wasn't even sad what happened to the outcome of the Ethan's character at the end. Once I noticed the obvious foreshadowing of the neighbor acting like she was jealous, I knew it was going to be the neighbor's attacking them.Â  It was a great concept, but to Hell with the budget. I've seen fan fiction videos on youtube with less of a budget that are way more amazing, with just 100 dollars and a decent affects studio. I would have liked to have the son from the first, be the main protagonist for this movie. It would have been cooler, to see what happened outside more. The "security footage" was poorly shot, and just basically repeating the same mundane type murders. It wasn't even a good "Thriller" movie, I scare easy, I wont deny I do. I laughed the whole movie, and nearly fell asleep in most parts. Such a disappointing movie, studios must be really desperate for franchise movies, I'd much rather have a sequel made from a good movie then a bad one. This one, I hope someone spoils the ending for me, so I can save 10 bucks for the theater. And Budget, is not an excuse for being lazy, with making a movie.Â

text: If this was a real thing then the world would look very different than it is portrayed in the movie. 1. A large portion of everyones lives would be dedicated to defense of property and self. I.E. bomb shelters, weapon stockpiles, fortresses, and very few traditional looking homes unless they are used as a lure.Â  2. no-one would use locks on doors like we do.Â  3. Honestly though there would not be that much murder because we would form social tribes and implement our own rules on people. Just because the government says there are no rules does not mean you can get away with anything it just means your more likely to get shot for doing small stuff instead of being arrested. It also means lynch mobs. Rules and laws are built into human nature.Â  Just think about it for two seconds. If you had a year to prepare for this what would you do. I personally would dig in to the point where it would take someone a month to dig me out with multiple escape tunnels in case they try and burn me out. I wouldn't buy a cheap looking lock from home depot and hope for the best. Or drive out somewhere the night of in my prius or whatever they were driving. And I definetely would not purchase some security system to protect me. Â

text: It's pretty good.Â  One guy looking for vengeance (because a drunk driver killed his son, and got off on a technicality)Â ends up with 4 survivors through the city.Â  They end up getting chased around by a couple of groups.Â  One is run by the government and is most equipped with 18 wheelers with mini-guns in the back and full swat type teams.Â  Another is a group with trucks and motorcycles which captures people and sells them to the rich that do their own "in-house" purge away for danger.Â  This last group caught the main 5 characters and sold them.Â  As they were hunted down by the highest bidders (7 of them), they killed 5 of the hunters.Â  The organizers got security to finish the hunt, but an anti-purge black panther type group busted in and saved the day.Â  One of the five main characters died in this battle.Â  After this, the guy looking for vengeance still went and tried to kill his target, but spared him.Â  After he left that house, one of the government hunter groups caught up to him and before a gunfight, but the purge time was over and he survived.

text: Everyone keeps say stuff about "why do they mention murder? Its like they want people to die." Ugh. Lets have an English lesson. The definition of "purge" is the mass removal of something (people) at a moments notice. Purge literally means getting rid of a mass amount of people without warning.  In this movie, They used it as a law in order to keep the population down AND control crime rates throughout the rest of the year.  On top of that, this "real purge" shit thats going around isnt gunna happen. T would be constitutionally impossible for the government to do this, and if a bunch of teenagers decided to put masks on and flash their airsoft guns, it wouldn't last to long anyway. Meanwhile, if you really are scared,  then hide your kids and hide your wives.

text: Â  I love reading fan fiction, where people add or change things in their favorite movie stories. I would love to see The Purge mixed in with other movie ideas, Purge Fan Fiction Crossovers. The first one I'd like to see is one dealing with The Expendables, where they are caught in the wake of a new experimental weapon, and are transported from Earth Prime to the world of The Purge. There, they have to survive, and defend as many innocents as they can, before they can find their way back to Earth Prime. The second idea would deal with Batman, where he is hit by an experimental weapon, but instead of dying he is transported to the world of The Purge, where he must defend the innocent, and discovers that the Bruce Wayne of Purge Earth is evil, and becomes Batman only for the night of The Purge, where he hunts the poor using his gadgets and fighting prowess, and the Bruce Wayne/Batman of Earth Prime must fight and stop him, Bruce Wayne must battle Bruce Wayne! The third idea would deal with Black Widow and Hawkeye, where they accidentally trigger a new Hydra device, and are transported to Purge Earth, where they discover that Hydra agents are there testing new weapons on people, all under the guise of being people who are Purging. The Black Widow and Hawkeye must stop them, and survive the other hunter teams out to kill them! The fourth idea would deal with Daredevil and The Punisher, where they are transported to Purge Earth, and must discover how they got there, and survive long enough to find their way home! And finally, I would like to see the crew of The Serenity, transported back to Earth That Was, and must find the parts to fix their crashed ship, and survive the night against hunter teams. But they have a weapon the hunter teams don't have: River Tam!

In this this one theyÂ show all kinds of crazy and wacky ass shit happening in the city during the purge. The characters are also likable and it has really fun and imaginative designs for some of the purgers. The plot was a little weak, but at the same time it'sÂ not likeÂ I watchÂ The Purge for a mind blowing plot. It is however suitable and I like the touch of psychotic state employed death squads. Did not care for the underground resistance sub-plot, but the film doesn't really loose it's narrative when focusing on them. This film isÂ better than it's predecessor and MUCH better than it's sequel.

Not to mention LOTS of people would be moving away from America since on that one goddamn day they cannot trust anyone, their families, friends, lovers just ANYONE without worrying they might kill them.
